{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_hoh_ver01/data/sn87093220/00200290409/1908033001/0170.xml":{"full_text":"4\nSemi-WeekJy\nAlwrrtiMMi Hernia.\nPubUslK'il ovpry M\"iiinv and Thur\u00dfilay\nat 10.- KasU Wislikiili Stri'it.\nTelephone 3541.\nJWO. J. CAitNEY. Editor and proprietor.\nI-,it. i-.-l at tlx- I'xst\u2022 'ffioo at AIK-rilron,\ni Kill matter.\ni,s SI \"111 I 'Tli >N 11 ATMS. {<>oo\nOn\u00ab* \\QQ\nSix ino'it lis i\nOne year. cash in mlvaueo\noffice.\nr-m>v t>r vis. nnst 1)0 in not later\nthS\" I Sat,...lay m for Monday\nunci V/e Ines.Liy noon for the lss.ie\nThnraday.\nThe Hor aid is the oldest paper on\nGrays Harbor, and has a i circu\nlation than any other piper in hehahs\ncounty. Advertis'.nu arc\nbased upon this claim ot circulation\nand a'l money due on contracts execu\nted under this statement will be tor\nleited it tho statement be not absolute\nly true.\nAll Citv Legal Notices are\nPublished in this paper.\nCitizen's Ticket.\nFor Clerk F- Chirk\nCOl NCI LM UN\nFirst ward Pressey\nSecond ward Win. Irvine\nThird ward Carney\nFourth ward Coxey\nFifth ward H. Kmpey\nSixth ward W Pierre\n..Strove S.grl. yl.cmfwyp cmfwyp\nWORKING- THE LABEL.\nTito editor of the lli:nAt.n, as candi\ndate for councilman. addressed a let tot'\nto oueh voter in the third ward, ex\npressing homo views upon i it\\ gov\neminent. One of those letters was\nreturned with the inquiry as to the\nreason the Typographical I'liion label\nwas not placed upon it.\nIn reply, wliieh is made puhlie for\nthe information of all. we will sa\\\nthat we are not \"working the union\nabcl to catch votes. We are operat\ning a union printing cilice, paying\nunion wages, and more, and, as we\ndo not parade the label on our ordi\nnary stationer) use 011 this par\nticular letter could only ha\\e been\nconstrued as a cheap attempt to\n\"work\" the union \\o!er. a style of\ncampaigning we deem beneath the\ndignity el the next eouneilman troni\nthe Third ward.\nA word to the anonymous corre\nspondent. 110 not again permit your\ncritical disposition to eause infringe\nment of the postal laws. Your letter\ncontaining writing' was mailed with a\none-cent stamp, and was a clear vio\nlation of the law \"in such cases made\nan 1 provided.\"\nCREOSOTED PAVEMENT.\nThere ha> just boon issued from tin\nforest service at Washington a circu\nlar referring to recent successes in\nthe employment of eroosotod wooden\nblocks for pavement. Tho forest\nservice believes that with a better\nknowledge of the fitness of some\n\"Woods and the effect of preservatives\non durability it is'almost certain the\nlino of wood will increase.\nSuggestions as to the best method\nof using wood favor rectangular\nblocks, thoroughly seasoned and pre\nserved from decay with creosote.\nJSnough of the oil is injected to re\nduce to a minimum the absorption of\nwater and consequent expansion and\ncontraction of the pavement. The\nl>lock> are laid with the grain vertical\nover an accurately surfaced cushion\non a solid foundation of cement-con\ncrete. They are close jointed, and in\nthe best practice the joints are made\nwater proof. The result is said to be\na pavement which is smooth, quiet,\nresilient. sanitary, easily cleaned and\neasily rspaired.\nThe cost of creosoted wood pave\nment in the I'nited States has varied\nfrom $i.40 to a square yard.\nNotwithstanding the high tirst cost\nthe forest service thinks there are\nconsiderations of service and durabil\nity that materially increase the differ\nence in favor of i reosoted wood.\nThere is in the I'nited States, how\never. almost r.o wood pavement of\nthe modern kir.d which lias yet been\ndown long enough to show its dura\nbility.\nA LESSON FOR ADVERTISERS.\nAs an instance of the value ofnews\ni paper advertising to increase or force\ntrade, the following facts are remark\nable. I luring December the orders\nreceived by the Douglas Boot it Shoe\ncompany, of Brockton, Mass., fell oil\njin consequence of the business de\npression following the panic. Ihe\nadvertising manager of that large\nconcern mentioned the matter to\nj Governor Douglas, and asked his ad\nvice, whether under the circumstances\nJ they sliotilil place the usual amount\nof advertising during January and\nFebruary, which are usually the slow\nest months in the year in the shoe\nbusiness. Governor Douglas at once\ni\u2022ordered an increase of 30 per cent in\nthe amount appropriated for adver\ni tising, declaring that such an increasi\nwould help to overcome the unfavor\nable business outlook. There was\nconsiderable skepticism about the re\nsult among the principal employes ot\nthe Douglas company. But the result\nI showed almost an immediate improve-\nI ment in business, which is now aver\nj aging more than last year during thesi\nJ unusually dull months.\nThus the business sagacity of Gov\ni ernor Douglas has overcome the hard\ntimes, and his optimism lias proven\nj an ant idote to the panic.\nThe advertising manager of Gov-\nI\ni ernor Douglas explains the phenome\nnon! of increased sales, when by all\ni the rules of business there should have\n_ l\nbeen a decrease, as entirely produced\nby the increased advertising. Other\nadvertisers of shoes were drawing in\nj their horns and mae.v of their ens-'\ni toiners were induced to patronize the\nDouglas Shoe because it was more\nthan ever brought to their notice.\nREFORMING FROM WITHIN.\nOregon wholesale liquor dealers\nhave taken upon themselves the work\nof ridding the retail branch of that\n1 business of such features as are serv\ning to promote the prohibition move\nment. They propose to drive out the\ndives, discountenance \"blind pigs,\"\nprosecute the sellers of liquor to\nminors and habitual drunkards, and\neffect a general el< ailing up of condi\ntions which serve to bring the busi\nness into disrepute. Reformers will\nfind that they have enlisted the co\noperation of the most powerful intlu\neiice which could be brought to bear\nin ameliorating the evils of intemper\nance if the plan is carried out, for the\nsurest method of working a change in\nau\\ branch of business is through the\nmedium of the men engaged ill it,\nwhile the liquor dealers have adopted\na plan which promises better results\nfor themselves than a continuance\nof efforts to dominate legislation\nand local policies, while tolerating the\ntlagrant violation of existing laws.\n\u2014West Coast Trade.\nAt the present tinu when the peo\nple of Washington are urging new\ncomers to find their homes in the Ev\nergreen State, advertising ideas are\nvaluable and probably one of the most\neffective pieces of high-grade, com\nmon-sense advertising that has been\nissued is a collection by Mr. J. li.\nShepard, under the title \"One Thous\nand Facts of Production.\"' It is a\ncompilation made up from reports of\nfarmers who live in the Willamette\nValley of Oregon, giving in a plain,\nblunt, common-sense way the state\nments of the individual growers ot\nfruit, vegetables, poultry and eggs,\ngrasses, cereal, hops, tobacco, nuts,\nlive-stock, etc. This compilation\nshould be in the hands of every news\npaper man as well as every officer ol\na commercial body throughout the\nstate of Washington, as the circula\ntion of similar facts about any part 01\nWashington would be of great value\nEditor Kibbe lias sold the Elma\nChronicle and retired from the editor\nial tripod, after more than twenty\nyears spent in the harness. With his\nvitrolio pen. Editor Kibbe was a force\nfor clean politics in Chehalis county,\nand his retirement will not be mourned\nby the would-be bosses and shirking\ni officials.\nA St. Louis exchange reports that a\nyoung man wearing three coats and\nfours pairs of trousers was taken into\ncustody by the police. It must be a\ncrime to wear too many elotlu in St.\ni Louis.\nABfxpi&H, Monday.\"march 30>, i9os.\nSUPT. BRYAN DYING.\nState Supt. of Instruction R. B. Bryan\nReported Dying at His Farm\nNear Yakima.\nNORTH YAKIMA, March\nState Superintendent of Instru tion\nK. I!. Bryan lies in a critical condi\ntion tonight at his ranch near VVap\nato and it is feared lie will not re\ncover. He was found unconscious by\nan irrigation ditch by his wife yes\nterday. His condition is said to have\nbeen caused by a blood clot, on the\nbrain. Physicians attending him say\nthere is not much chance for his re\ncovery.\nLater His son, K. \\Y. llryan, of\nthis cltv, received a telegram this\nmorning announcing the death of his\nfather last night. The remains will\nbe brought to Montesano, his former\nhome, for burial.\nSOUTHERN LINES NOT SHUT OUT.\nRuling' of Interstate Commerce Com\nmission Is Modified\u2014Southern\nWill Ticket to Sound.\nSAN FRANCISCO. March L'S.\u2014A\ntelegram was received at the general\noffice of the Southern Pacific com\npany in this city today from Charles\nS. Fee, passenger traffic manager,\nwho is at present in Chicago, an\nnouncing that the recent action of\nthe interstate commerce commission\nwhich was interpreted as closing the\nj Portland gateway and necessitating a\nhigher passenger rate by the Soulli\nern Pacific to Tacoma ami Seattle and\n!other Northern points via Portland\nhas been modified. The objection of\nthe commission, it appears, related\nonly to the manner of publishing\nthrough rates, and revised tariffs\nconforming to Ihe commission's\nwishes will lie issued as soon as pos\nsible.\nThis new ruling will be received\nwith great satisfaction in Portland,\nwhich was being adversely affected\nby the higher passenger rates charged\nfrom the Fast to Seattle via. Portland\nthan were charged to Seattle over\nthe Great Northern. The Southern\nPacific is equally pleased, for it h:.s 1\nbeen known that iis earnings and i\nprestige have suffered by the former\nrates.\nTHE AEEKDEEN COLONY.\nAberdeen Residents at long Beach.\nCal., Are Having a Jolly Good\nTime.\nMr. and Mrs. K. C. Wheeler, who\nhave recently become residents of\nthis city, are residing at Ills' Locust\navenue, entertained at dinner yester\nday in honor of Washington friends\nwho have been spending the winter\ni\nin Long Reach and return soon. The j\nguests were Mr. and Mrs. A. 11. Far-;\nnam, Mrs. H. M. Cook and daughter j\nElizabeth. Mr. Charles Sutlers. Mr.\nand Mrs. X. G. Wheeler. Mrs. Ida L. j\nWheeler.\nThe parlors were prettily decorated\nwith roses and lilies and the center\npiece was of freesias. Following din\nner there were social diversions of\na delightful sort. The out-of-town\nguests will return to Aberdeen short\nly.\u2014l.ong Beach Press.\nALONG THE WATERFRONT.\nReport of Arrivals and Departures of\nVessels and Those Loading at\nthe Mills.\nThe brig Geneva is loading at the'\nWilson mill for San Francisco.\nThe steamers (.'armel and Coronado\nleft San Francisco for Aberdeen Sat-'\nurday. I\nThe schooner MarUuna is at the'\nSlade mill, loading for Wellington,\nNew Zealand.\nThe schooner William Kenton is\nat the Slade mill loading for Santa\nRosalia, Mexico.\nThe barkentine S. C. Allen is at\nthe Anderson Middleton mill load\ning for Honolulu.\nThe British steamer Indravelli is\nloading at the Slade mill for Sidney,\nNew South Wales.\nThe schooner Meteor is loading at\nthe Aberdeen Lumber Shingle\nmills for San Pedro.\nThe schooner Expansion is at the\nAberdeen Lumber Shingle mills,\nloading for San Francisco.\ni\nThe schooner Susie Plummer arrived\nin port last night, to load at the Aber\ndeen Lumber \u00abSc Shingle mills for Cal\nlao. Peru.\nThe schooner Annie Campbell is\nloading at the Aberdeen Lumber\nj Shingle mills for Guaymas, Mexico.\nLame Shoulder.\nWhether resulting from a sprain\nor from rheumatic pains, there is\nnothing so good for a lame shoulder\nas Chamberlain's Pain Balm. Apply\nit freely and rub the parts vigorous\nly at each application and a quick\ncure is certain. For sale by Evans\nDrug Co.\nrot\nwr S*r\ni\ni. 1 I\ni t-\ni\n\ni\nSw\n_\ni\n'f\nVs:-'\n\nV V V\n:<a\nV- *I-\n\\V J\n15| 1\nm)\nFORM ONE\ni\nThe FECHHEI.X.LK 11SHEL CO.\nNEW YORK\nMrararsi\nM\u00bbke Your of\nSpring\nClothes\n\\(nv iiii<l Avoid tlio Itnsli\nof the \"Eleventh Hour\" buy\ners. The style and fabric range\nis now complete and every gar\nment is worthy of examination\nof your wearing.\nColiegEsn\nSpring Suits\nAt $15 to $30\nArc recognized as the standard\nof style, service and economy;\nin fact they measure up to the\nhighest, standard set by Amer\nica's best custom tailors. It is\nto your interest to examine\nand try on the new models of\nthis famous make. Do it today, i\nA. W. BERKLEY\n203 G Street, Kberdeen, Wn.\nTHE BURGOMASTER.\nFamous Musical Masterpiece at the\nGrand Next Thursday Evening.\nPixlev Luder's merry musical\nmasterpiece, \"The Burgomaster,\" the\nfirst and greatest success of these\nclever writers will come to the Grand\ntheater Thursday, April 2. Of all the\nmusical shows that annually visit\nAberdeen none find more genuine\nfavor than \"The Burgomaster.\"\nThere are some twenty-odd \"musical\ngems\" in this really meritorious offer\nings. A company of superior excel\nlence. including the original Gus\nWeinburg and Ruth White, has been\nengaged, along with some of the\nprettiest singing chorus in America,\nand with the famous Kangaroo Girls\nwill form one of the strongest musi\ncal attractions to visit us this year.\nTHE WORLD DRYING UP.\nPossibility That the Human Race Will\nDie of Thirst.\nWe are to die of thirst. Compara\ntively few persons know the suffering'\ninvolved in a thirst for which there i* j\nno help at hand. The consuming thirst.\nmore than the pain of any wound\nmakes the battlefield a hell. Yet death\nby thirst is the doom forecast for tls\u2022 j\nrace by grim scientists. Geologist;-:\nfind that the fresh water supply of tlu j\nglobe is falling. They have data which j\npoint to the gradual withdrawal of tlu\nstreams and other bodies of watet:\nfrom the surface. Both in Africa and\ncentral Asia and. indeed. in all the\ngreat levels the water beds are drying\nup. A great number of lakes well\nknown in the historical age have en\ntirely disappeared. For example. Lake\nChiroua, in Africa, has vanished with\nin recent years, as has also Lake\nNgamJ, discovered by Livingstone\nLake Tchad is more than half dried\nup. For centuries bodies of water 1\"\ncentral Asia have been evaporating\nand the deserts extending. When\n2,000 years ago great cities stood tn\neast Turkestan there are found only\nvast and depressing stretches of sand\nThe river Tarim, once a principal Asi\natic route, is almost gone, ami Lob-\nNor, formerly four times the area of\nLake Geneva, is now but a shallow\nmarsh. The same sad conditions are\nnoted in European Russia. Novgorod,\nthe most pushing city in the czar's dls\ntraded realm, was surrounded by wa\nter in the middle ages. While we may\nbe sure that the fate which the geolo\ngic- sr.L-.est for humanity is very fat\naway, the facts recited to show the\ndrying up pro ess are convincing proofs\nof \"the need of preserving our forests\nwith more care. St. Paul Pioneer\nTress.\nWOLFF'S\nAtontmi's Largest an<l llesl More\nGuaranteed Silk Petticoats\n$8.50 Values for $6.50\nY\\ I'\" J ust received a large sliipinent of S. 11. &M.\nW guarateed silk petticoats, the choicest and best\nvalues it has ever been our privilege to offer. We have\nover three thousand dollars worth of brand new f-esh\nsilk petticoats just from the factory, every one of them\nis guaranteed to give satisfaction, if not we give von a\nnew one in return. All shades of brown, Copenhagen\nblues, Leather shades, green, red, greys, blacks and\nwhites, and all other shades desired, in plaid tailor made\nand fancy silks. Some of them are protected with S\nH. M. binding.\n0,1 Sa, X()W\n/o\\\\ $8.50\nL Petticoats\nJ $6.50\nWe have skirts to\nfit the smallest as\nwell as the stoutest\nOur guarantee\u2014-\nShould this petticoat\n\u25a0yjjr dale ot l nircllast -N re\n\nwill give you a new\none.\nGEO. J. WOLFF\nt Aberdeen's Largest and Best Store\nSuperior Stoves and Manges\nAre the BEST\n6ood Bakers and Last a Lifetime\nSOLD B